#. type: Title #
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_introduction.Rmd:1
#: reports/Reference-Report/content/_introduction.Rmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Introduction"
msgstr "Λύση"

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_introduction.Rmd:3
#, no-wrap
msgid "This is a [NeoIPC Surveillance](https://neoipc.org/surveillance/ \"Link to the surveillance section of the NeoIPC website\") analysis that you can use to assess infection rates in your neonatal unit. If you have your own data collected using the same or a comparable method, you can compare them with the reference values presented in this document and identify any anomalies and potential for improvement.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_fig-intro-birth-weight.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Birth weight distribution is a key indicator of your unit's patient population characteristics. Understanding the weight distribution of admitted neonates helps contextualize infection rates and other outcomes, as lower birth weight is associated with increased vulnerability to healthcare-associated infections. This figure shows both the frequency distribution (histogram with density curve) and summary statistics (boxplot with quartiles) of birth weights in your unit, enabling comparison with your patient case mix relative to reference data when available.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_fig-intro-gestational-age.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Gestational age distribution provides essential context for interpreting clinical outcomes in your neonatal unit. Extremely premature infants face substantially higher risks of complications and infections compared to more mature neonates. This figure illustrates both the frequency distribution (histogram with density curve) and summary statistics (boxplot with quartiles) of gestational ages at birth, allowing you to assess how your patient population's maturity profile compares to reference data when available.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_tbl-intro-incidence-density.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "This table presents the incidence density rates for the most important healthcare-associated infections (HAI) in your neonatal unit. Incidence density rates are calculated per 1,000 patient days, allowing for meaningful comparison between units with different patient volumes and lengths of stay. Regular monitoring of these rates enables you to identify trends, evaluate the effectiveness of infection prevention measures, and compare your performance against reference data from other participating units.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_tbl-intro-device-associated.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Device-associated infections represent a significant burden in neonatal intensive care. This table shows infection rates specifically linked to the use of invasive devices such as central venous catheters and mechanical ventilation. By tracking device-associated infection rates separately, you can assess the safety of device utilization in your unit and identify specific areas where targeted interventions may reduce infection risk. Lower rates may indicate successful implementation of device care bundles and infection prevention protocols.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_tbl-intro-agent-per-infection.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Understanding which pathogens cause infections in your unit is essential for targeted prevention strategies and empirical treatment decisions. This table presents the detection rates of infectious agents per infection type, highlighting the microbial epidemiology of healthcare-associated infections in your neonatal population. Patterns in pathogen distribution can inform antimicrobial stewardship efforts and help identify potential sources of transmission requiring specific control measures.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_tbl-intro-abr-infection.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Antimicrobial resistance poses a critical threat to vulnerable neonatal patients. This table displays infection rates caused by resistant pathogens such as MRSA, VRE, and third-generation cephalosporin-resistant organisms. Monitoring these rates is crucial for assessing the burden of drug-resistant infections in your unit and evaluating the effectiveness of antimicrobial stewardship programs. Elevated rates may signal the need for enhanced infection control measures, antibiotic prescribing review, or environmental screening protocols.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_tbl-intro-infectious-agent-detection.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "The pattern of pathogen detection across different infection types provides valuable insights into your unit's microbial ecology. This table shows how frequently specific infectious agents are identified in various types of healthcare-associated infections. Understanding these detection patterns helps in developing targeted surveillance strategies, appropriate empirical therapy guidelines, and infection prevention protocols tailored to your unit's specific pathogen profile.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_tbl-intro-resistance-test.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Antimicrobial resistance testing is fundamental to both individual patient management and population-level surveillance. This table presents the rate at which pathogens isolated from infections undergo resistance testing. High testing rates ensure reliable data for antimicrobial stewardship programs and enable accurate assessment of resistance trends. Lower rates may indicate gaps in microbiological diagnostic capacity or protocols that could limit your ability to detect and respond to emerging resistance patterns.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_tbl-intro-risk-density.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Risk factors and protective factors significantly influence infection outcomes in neonatal care. This table shows the utilization density of key interventions including invasive devices (which increase infection risk) and protective measures such as human milk feeding, kangaroo care, and probiotics. Benchmarking these utilization rates helps identify opportunities to reduce unnecessary device use while optimizing evidence-based protective interventions. The balance between risk and protective factors reflects your unit's overall approach to infection prevention.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_tbl-intro-surgical-procedure.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Surgical procedures represent a major risk factor for healthcare-associated infections in neonatal intensive care. This table presents rates of various surgical procedures performed in your unit, normalized per 1,000 patient days. Understanding your surgical case mix is essential for interpreting infection rates and implementing appropriate surgical site infection prevention protocols. Comparison with reference data helps contextualize your unit's surgical workload and associated infection risks.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: reports/Partner-Report/content/_tbl-intro-secondary-bsi.qmd:1
#, no-wrap
msgid "Secondary bloodstream infections occur when primary infections at other sites seed the bloodstream, representing serious complications that significantly impact patient outcomes. This table shows the rate at which different primary infection types progress to secondary bloodstream involvement. High rates of secondary BSI may indicate delayed diagnosis, inadequate source control, or particularly virulent pathogens, and warrant careful review of clinical protocols and infection management strategies.\n"
msgstr ""

